<section id="fb1">
  <p class="feedbacktext">1. This means 'during' the decade.</p>
</section>

<section id="fb2">
  <p class="feedbacktext">2. 'At' is used with time. 'At four o'clock', for example.</p>
  <p class="feedbacktext">'On' is used with days of the week. 'On Tuesday', for example.</p>
</section>

<section id="fb3">
  <p class="feedbacktext">3. In other words, up to 1995.</p>
</section>

<section id="fb4">
  <p class="feedbacktext">4. In other words, from 1996 to 1998.</p>
</section>

<section id="fb5">
  <p class="feedbacktext">5. 'At' is used with time. 'At four o'clock', for example.</p>
  <p class="feedbacktext">We usually use 'by' with perfect tenses. 'By 1992 the figures had risen.', for example.</p>
</section>

<section id="fb6">
  <p class="feedbacktext">6. This means 'during' the rest of the period.</p>
</section>

<section id="fb7">
  <p class="feedbacktext">7. The word 'times' in the sentence refers to clock hours during the day, so we use the proposition 'at'.</p>
</section>

<section id="fb8">
  <p class="feedbacktext">8. 'In' is used for years, not days of the week.</p>
  <p class="feedbacktext">'At' is used for the hour, not days of the week.</p>
</section>

<section id="fb9">
  <p class="feedbacktext">9. 'During' is used with periods of time, not a single point in time.</p>
  <p class="feedbacktext">'To' is usually used with 'from' to refer to a period of time. 'From 2 o'clock to half past 3', for example.</p>
</section>

<section id="fb10">
  <p class="feedbacktext">10. We use 'between' with two dates or times to refer to a period.</p>
  <p class="feedbacktext">With this preposition, the sentence doesn't agree with the figures in the chart. 'Until' would mean that 'prime time' came to an end in the evening.</p>
</section>

<section id="fb11">
  <p class="feedbacktext">11. 'In' is used for years, not hours of the day.</p>
  <p class="feedbacktext">'During' is used with periods of time, not a single point in time.</p>
</section>

<section id="fb12">
  <p class="feedbacktext">12. Also look at gap 13.</p>
</section>

<section id="fb13">
  <p class="feedbacktext">13. Also look at gap 12.</p>
</section>

<section id="fb14">
  <p class="feedbacktext">14. Midnight is a point of time, not an extended period.</p>
  <p class="feedbacktext">We usually use 'by' with perfect tenses. 'By 1 o'clock most viewers had switched off and gone to bed', for example.</p>
</section>

<section id="fb15">
  <p class="feedbacktext">15. In other words, by the time 3 a.m. is reached, very few people are still watching.</p>
</section>

<section id="fb16">
  <p class="feedbacktext">16. In other words, viewing figures remain low and do not rise before 10 a.m.</p>
</section>

<section id="fb17">
  <p class="feedbacktext">17. In this sentence 'over' means 'during'.</p>
</section>

<section id="fb18">
  <p class="feedbacktext">18. 'In' is used for years.</p>
</section>

<section id="fb19">
  <p class="feedbacktext">19. This is also correct for 'During' or 'In', but they don't agree with the information in the chart.</p>
</section>

<section id="fb20">
  <p class="feedbacktext">20. Also look at gap 21.</p>
</section>

<section id="fb21">
  <p class="feedbacktext">21. Also look at gap 20.</p>
</section>

<section id="fb22">
  <p class="feedbacktext">22. This is an example of using 'by' with the past perfect tense.</p>
</section>

<section id="examtips">
  <p class="popuptext">When describing trends over time, you must be careful with the prepositions of time you use.</p>
</section>

